[
  "G'day. I'm Mick Baker, Head of Conversion at Employment Hero. Over the next fifteen minutes I'm going to show you how a team of two went from shipping ten A/B tests in a whole year to more than twenty in a single month — by rebuilding our operating system around AI instead of bolting AI onto a broken one. This is a joint session with Optimizely; a lot of what I'll show you rides on top of their platform.",
  "Before we start — a question. How many experiments is your team running right now? Not planned. Not sitting in a backlog waiting for a sprint. Actually live, in-market, reading data. Keep that number in your head. We'll come back to it.",
  "Most teams I talk to are doing what I'll call AI-adjacent work. Faster drafts, a chatbot in a Slack channel, maybe summarised meeting notes — but the underlying workflow hasn't moved. The same six people still have to approve the same thing. That's very different from AI-first, which is what we've done at Employment Hero. We didn't speed up the workflow. We rebuilt it. AI is the execution layer now, not a helper.",
  "Very quickly on who we are. Employment Hero is a global HR, payroll and benefits platform. We operate across ANZ — where we're headquartered — the UK, and Canada. Conversion, as a function, is brand new inside the business. Team of two. That context matters, because every decision I'm about to describe was made under real constraints, not abstract ambition.",
  "Here's the problem we inherited. I call it test paralysis. It's that creeping feeling that the data you actually need to make a decision is always one more approval cycle away. Research. Brief. Design. Copy. Engineering. Eventually live — if nothing slips. Six weeks to learn one thing. By the time you learn it, the question's already changed.",
  "And this was our ceiling. Ten to twelve A/B tests per year. That's not a headcount issue — two great practitioners can't out-run a queue. It's a system issue. The machine we were operating inside had a maximum throughput, and we had hit it.",
  "Before I talk about the product we built, three things I had to accept. First — think like a product builder, not a service team. Stop taking tickets and start shipping your own thing. Second — scale the process before you grow the team. Hiring more people into a broken workflow just makes the breakage more expensive. And third — and this is the real one — the goal isn't faster tests. The goal is reclaiming strategic thinking. Velocity buys back the thing a conversion team never has: time to think.",
  "This is what we built. We call it the Conversion Hub. One interface. One source of truth. AI as the execution layer, not a chat window in the corner. Everything I show you from here on out lives inside it.",
  "This is what's connected underneath. Five layers. On the left — our inputs: Miro, Hotjar, documents. Up top — the intelligence: Claude and Claude Code. Below — the workflow: Asana, Sheets, Confluence. On the right — execution, led by Optimizely, with Figma actually on the way out. And distribution back to Slack and our live dashboard. The Hub sits in the middle. It's the only place a human touches.",
  "This is the front door to it. The programme dashboard. Win rate, average lift, annualised MQLs, revenue impact — all live. I don't build reports anymore. If there's a bottleneck in the pipeline, it's visible in seconds, not assembled at the end of the quarter.",
  "This is the research app. You point it at raw data — a Miro board, Hotjar exports, an interview PDF — and Claude produces an experiment-ready brief on the other side. Observation, how-might-we, hypothesis, test direction. The important bit is this: the hypothesis that actually goes live is the same one that came out of the research. No Chinese whispers. No dilution across four handoffs.",
  "From the brief, three agents take over. A designer — mocks to spec against our brand tokens. A copywriter — three variations per block, each with a different psychological angle. A developer — Claude Code, writing variation code and pushing it straight into Optimizely. The agents execute. The humans direct. The creative call, the brand call, the strategic call — those stay with us.",
  "The integration with Optimizely is the one I want to spend a moment on. Claude Code generates variation code configured for Optimizely's architecture. It pushes via the API. Tracking is wired — standard metrics or a custom event API, generated to spec. The test goes live, Slack gets notified on the right market channel, and our Weekly Pulse pulls the results into a structured update. What used to take thirty-plus days — getting into a dev sprint, getting tracking right, getting it live — now happens in minutes.",
  "And this is the result. Through most of 2024, roughly a test a month. Flat. You can see where the Conversion Hub went live. The curve kicks. February, seventeen. March — twenty-plus tests in a single month. More tests in one month than we'd run in the entire prior year.",
  "Where this is going. We want Conversion to be a global standard, not a central bottleneck. A learning hub that trains any market team on the platform. Any market can run experiments to the ANZ standard. The central team shifts from doing the work to setting the direction. Local execution. Global alignment.",
  "One thing I want to be very clear about. AI-first does not mean human-last. The failure mode here is producing faster, blander output — optimising your way into mediocrity. Creative direction stays human. Brand originality stays human. We're not chasing faster slop. We're chasing faster good.",
  "Quickly on the commercial case, because I know someone in the room is running the numbers. Team of two doing the work of roughly ten. Running cost is about a hundred and fifty to two hundred US dollars a month. Two to three hours a week back from admin alone. And critically — no reliance on a global function to stand up or run tests. Ownership sits where the work happens.",
  "So. Twelve tests a year. Twenty-plus in a month. A team of two. If you take one thing away tonight — don't hire your way out of a workflow problem. Build your way out of it. Thanks very much."
